===============================================================================
 LLVM Patch: Lower Xava Builtins to Custom IR Intrinsics / TableGen Patterns
===============================================================================

File: clang/lib/CodeGen/CGBuiltin.cpp

Add the RISC-V Xava switch cases inside `EmitRISCVBuiltinExpr`:

--- a/clang/lib/CodeGen/CGBuiltin.cpp
+++ b/clang/lib/CodeGen/CGBuiltin.cpp
@@ -xxx,8 +xxx,44 @@
 Value *CodeGenFunction::EmitRISCVBuiltinExpr(unsigned BuiltinID,
                                              const CallExpr *E,
                                              ReturnValueSlot ReturnValue) {
   switch (BuiltinID) {
+  // --- AVA Custom Instructions (Xava) ---
+  case RISCV::BI__builtin_riscv_xava_vpdot:
+  case RISCV::BI__builtin_riscv_xava_vpdot4:
+  case RISCV::BI__builtin_riscv_xava_vdot:
+  case RISCV::BI__builtin_riscv_xava_vmacc:
+  case RISCV::BI__builtin_riscv_xava_vrequant: {
+    // 3 vector operands: vd, vs2, vs1 (or rs1 for vrequant)
+    // In inline asm logic, lowering can just emit the correct asm pattern,
+    // or if we map to custom LLVM intrinsics, it calls Intrinsic::riscv_xava_*
+    // For simplicity in keeping the compiler oblivious, we often map these to
+    // inline asm directly in CodeGen or to specific LLVM IR intrinsics.
+    Value *VD = EmitScalarExpr(E->getArg(0));
+    Value *VS2 = EmitScalarExpr(E->getArg(1));
+    Value *VS1 = EmitScalarExpr(E->getArg(2));
+    Function *F = CGM.getIntrinsic(Intrinsic::riscv_xava_vpdot); // Example
+    return Builder.CreateCall(F, {VD, VS2, VS1});
+  }
+  case RISCV::BI__builtin_riscv_xava_vrelu:
+  case RISCV::BI__builtin_riscv_xava_vsigmoid:
+  case RISCV::BI__builtin_riscv_xava_vtanh: {
+    Value *VD = EmitScalarExpr(E->getArg(0));
+    Value *VS2 = EmitScalarExpr(E->getArg(1));
+    Function *F = CGM.getIntrinsic(Intrinsic::riscv_xava_vrelu);
+    return Builder.CreateCall(F, {VD, VS2});
+  }
+  case RISCV::BI__builtin_riscv_xava_vperf: {
+    Value *VD = EmitScalarExpr(E->getArg(0));
+    Function *F = CGM.getIntrinsic(Intrinsic::riscv_xava_vperf);
+    return Builder.CreateCall(F, {VD});
+  }

Notes:
  - This pseudocode assumes you define corresponding `Intrinsic::riscv_xava_*`
    in `llvm/include/llvm/IR/IntrinsicsRISCV.td`.
  - A much simpler and highly robust approach used by many accelerator teams
    (instead of full LLVM IR Custom Intrinsics) is to map the Clang Builtin
    directly to TableGen pseudo-inline-asm or directly generate the DAG node.
    Since we defined TableGen classes (VPDOT_VV etc) in RISCVInstrInfoXava.td,
    the compiler can auto-generate `IntrinsicsRISCVXava.td` mapping if we use
    the `ClangBuiltin` hook in the standard LLVM `def` pattern:

    def int_riscv_xava_vpdot : Intrinsic<[llvm_anyvector_ty],
      [llvm_anyvector_ty, llvm_anyvector_ty],
      [IntrNoMem]>; // in IntrinsicsRISCV.td
